II. Introduction
The concept of local space has been a topic of interest for many scholars, particularly in the fields of physics, psychology, and philosophy. Local space refers to the immediate surroundings and environment that individuals inhabit and perceive (Gibson, 1979). The relative nature of local space suggests that its apparent reality is influenced by various factors, rather than being an absolute construct. This research aims to investigate the factors contributing to the apparent reality of local space.  Providing background information and context, the concept of local space has been examined in various disciplines. In physics, local space is often discussed in relation to the theory of relativity, which suggests that the perception of space and time is relative to the observer's frame of reference (Einstein, 1905). Meanwhile, in psychology, local space has been studied in the context of perception, cognition, and behavior (Gibson, 1979). Moreover, in philosophy, local space has been considered in relation to metaphysics, epistemology, and phenomenology (Husserl, 1936).  The research problem or question at hand is to determine the factors contributing to the apparent reality of local space. While previous research has examined local space in various disciplines, there is a need for a comprehensive investigation of the factors contributing to its relative nature. Thus, this research aims to outline the research objectives and scope.  The research objectives are as follows:  1. To identify the factors contributing to the apparent reality of local space. 2. To examine the relationship between the identified factors and the perception of local space. 3. To explore the implications of the relative nature of local space for physics, psychology, and philosophy.  The scope of this research will be limited to a review of existing literature, theoretical analysis, and conceptual framework development. Empirical data collection and analysis will not be within the scope of this re