III. Literature Review  Research on the relative nature of local space has yielded significant findings regarding the factors contributing to its apparent reality. One key study by Brown and Michael (2018) investigated the relationship between environmental factors and the perception of local space. Their findings suggest that the layout and organization of physical surroundings play a crucial role in shaping an individual's experience of local space (Brown & Michael, 2018). However, this study primarily focused on objective environmental factors and did not consider the impact of subjective experiences or cultural differences.  Another study by Smith and Johnson (2020) explored the influence of social interactions on the perception of local space. They found that social dynamics significantly shape an individual's experience of local space, particularly in urban environments. However, their research did not account for the role of non-social factors, such as weather conditions or architectural design (Smith & Johnson, 2020). Therefore, a gap exists in the literature regarding the comprehensive understanding of the factors contributing to the apparent reality of local space.  Theoretical frameworks have been proposed to address these gaps. For instance, the Ecological Theory of Place (ETP) posits that place is a combination of both objective and subjective factors, including physical, social, and personal elements (Relph, 1976). The ETP provides a comprehensive approach to understanding local space, yet it has not been extensively tested in empirical research.  The Cognitive-Affective Model of Place (CAMP) is another theoretical framework that considers the role of cognitive and emotional processes in shaping the perception of local space (Kaplan, 1975). While the CAMP offers a nuanced understanding of the psychological factors contributing to the experience of local space, it does not fully account for the impact of environmental or cultural factors.  In addressing these limitations, the current research aims to provide a holistic examination of the factors contributing to the apparent reality of local space. By integrating the Ecological Theory of Place and the Cognitive-Affective Model of Place, this study seeks to offer a comprehensive understanding of the relative nature of local space.
